it's being pushed.

03:06.019 --> 03:08.855
‐ I'm designing
a drop point camp knife.

03:08.855 --> 03:11.233
<i>I can leave</i>
<i>a really thick spine</i>

03:11.233 --> 03:13.819
<i>and leave a pretty keen edge.</i>

03:13.819 --> 03:16.363
<i>I want to compete</i>
<i>to prove to myself</i>

03:16.363 --> 03:18.156
that I can hang
with the big dogs.

03:18.156 --> 03:20.117
‐ Now, they have to take
at least two different pieces

03:20.117 --> 03:23.036
of steel
from our gym setup

03:23.036 --> 03:25.414
and combine them
into that signature blade.

03:25.414 --> 03:27.165
‐ Yep, forge welding

03:27.165 --> 03:28.959
is definitely gonna be
necessary in this challenge.

03:28.959 --> 03:32.129
<i>‐ I feel that my work</i>
<i>is cut out for me</i>

03:32.129 --> 03:33.713
with these younger smiths,

03:33.713 --> 03:35.882
<i>but I think I can use</i>
<i>my experience</i>

03:35.882 --> 03:37.926
to try to gain an advantage.

03:37.926 --> 03:41.555
<i>I'm designing</i>
<i>a camp knife/bowie.</i>

03:41.555 --> 03:43.723
<i>I want it thick</i>
<i>at the cutting edge.</i>

03:43.723 --> 03:45.559
<i>I don't want</i>
<i>to have any problem</i>

03:45.559 --> 03:50.272
with the blade snapping
or the cutting edge chipping.

03:50.272 --> 03:53.567
‐ I am going to make a seax
so that I have a strong back

03:53.567 --> 03:55.777
<i>and a good slashing edge.</i>

03:55.777 --> 03:59.865
I think the barbell will fare
very well in the edge chop

03:59.865 --> 04:02.409
<i>because it's a good</i>
<i>high carbon steel.</i>

04:02.409 --> 04:04.786
Hm, that's
kind of hideous.

04:04.786 --> 04:06.663
‐ I'm drawing
a straight‐back seax.

04:06.663 --> 04:08.331
I know they didn't have

04:08.331 --> 04:10.250
<i>to have a real sharp point</i>
<i>for stabbing.</i>

04:10.250 --> 04:12.919
They just needed to be able
to cut and take some abuse.

04:12.919 --> 04:15.130
<i>I have actually used</i>
<i>gym equipment before</i>

04:15.130 --> 04:17.424
<i>and just made</i>
<i>some knives out of it.</i>

04:17.424 --> 04:19.801
<i>I know the leg lift</i>
<i>is a hardenable steel.</i>

04:19.801 --> 04:21.761
Frame?
Mild steel.

04:21.761 --> 04:24.639
<i>So I'm seeing</i>
<i>some good options.</i>

04:24.639 --> 04:26.933
‐ Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing.

04:26.933 --> 04:29.478
This design period is closed.

04:29.478 --> 04:32.022
Your three‐hour forge time
starts now.

04:32.022 --> 04:33.774
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:33.774 --> 04:36.777
‐ Off to the races.
‐ Cool, calm, and collected.

04:36.777 --> 04:38.278
<i>‐ Me and</i>
<i>the other contestants,</i>

04:38.278 --> 04:39.780
<i>we all kind of pitched in</i>

04:39.780 --> 04:41.782
and helped one another
get our steel.

04:41.782 --> 04:43.116
‐ Take the whole thing over.

04:43.116 --> 04:45.619
‐ How do y'all want
to chop it up?

04:45.619 --> 04:47.287
‐ Chop it off.
‐ Three equal pieces or what?

04:47.287 --> 04:48.663
‐ We'll park it
right over there.

04:48.663 --> 04:51.625
‐ So talk to me
about steel selection.

04:51.625 --> 04:53.001
‐ The barbell, I think

04:53.001 --> 04:55.295
the inner portion
is high carbon steel,

04:55.295 --> 04:58.465
and then anything outside
that holds the plates is mild.

04:58.465 --> 05:01.635
‐ How much do you want?
‐ I need to take 14.

05:01.635 --> 05:03.470
‐ Okay.

05:03.470 --> 05:05.806
<i>I think you can tell if</i>
<i>a steel is hardenable or not</i>

05:05.806 --> 05:07.682
by what it was used for.

05:07.682 --> 05:10.018
Is it being put under
a lot of stress?

05:10.018 --> 05:13.647
<i>Is it meant to flex</i>
<i>but not bend?</i>

05:13.647 --> 05:17.484
<i>I'm choosing the barbell</i>
<i>and the twisted barbell.</i>

05:17.484 --> 05:20.987
<i>The straight bar</i>
<i>has to hold more weight,</i>

05:20.987 --> 05:25.158
so I think the straight barbell
will be much harder steel

05:25.158 --> 05:26.827
<i>than the twisted barbell.</i>

05:26.827 --> 05:28.662
‐ At this stage,
you really want to get

05:28.662 --> 05:30.705
that high carbon steel flat
to get a good forge weld.

05:30.705 --> 05:34.835
It's difficult to weld
anything onto a round rod.

05:34.835 --> 05:37.546
<i>‐ I think making a San Mai</i>
<i>would be the easiest way</i>

05:37.546 --> 05:40.006
<i>to go about making the blade</i>
<i>I want to make,</i>

05:40.006 --> 05:42.050
<i>'cause it's the easiest way</i>
<i>to stack it up</i>

05:42.050 --> 05:44.511
<i>and get in the forge quickly.</i>

05:44.511 --> 05:46.012
<i>I've determined that</i>

05:46.012 --> 05:48.181
<i>the curved barbell</i>
<i>is softer steel,</i>

05:48.181 --> 05:52.227
<i>so I weld it onto the outer</i>
<i>side of the longer piece</i>

05:52.227 --> 05:55.188
<i>of hardenable steel</i>
<i>in the middle.</i>

05:55.188 --> 05:59.276
I'm a little nervous,
but I think I got this.

05:59.276 --> 06:01.862
‐ I have a round stock
of hardenable steel right now.

06:01.862 --> 06:06.700
‐ Steve, he's got a large piece
of the actual barbell.

06:06.700 --> 06:09.369
<i>‐ I'm gonna forge out my blade</i>
<i>from the barbell</i>

06:09.369 --> 06:11.204
<i>because it is hardenable steel</i>

06:11.204 --> 06:13.206
<i>and will giving me</i>
<i>a better cutting edge.</i>

06:13.206 --> 06:15.709
I'm gonna worry
about the mild steel

06:15.709 --> 06:18.378
<i>after I get my blade</i>
<i>and my tang</i>

06:18.378 --> 06:20.714
<i>roughed out</i>
<i>to where I like it.</i>

06:20.714 --> 06:22.632
<i>I'm the old‐timer</i>
<i>in this crew.</i>

06:22.632 --> 06:24.885
I'm not gonna try to outgun
these kids,

06:24.885 --> 06:26.553
but I'm gonna
try to outsmart 'em.

06:26.553 --> 06:30.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:30.015 --> 06:34.436
‐ Jake has grabbed one
of the bars to the dumbbell.

06:34.436 --> 06:36.646
‐ I've seen people put
900 pounds on that thing,

06:36.646 --> 06:38.732
and it flex but never break,

06:38.732 --> 06:41.026
<i>so I know that it's gonna be</i>
<i>a good high carbon steel.</i>

06:41.026 --> 06:43.028
‐ I'm gonna do
a San Mai Damascus

06:43.028 --> 06:46.239
<i>with the mild steel from the</i>
<i>casing of the bench itself.</i>

06:46.239 --> 06:47.574
‐ Jake's doing
a San Mai technique

06:47.574 --> 06:49.409
just like Braxton did.

06:49.409 --> 06:51.703
The technique is smart,
because that softer mild steel

06:51.703 --> 06:53.913
will provide a shock absorber
for the harder steel,

06:53.913 --> 06:55.790
which could help
during testing.

06:55.790 --> 06:57.584
<i>‐ It's super important</i>
<i>to get your steel cleaned</i>

06:57.584 --> 06:58.918
<i>before you do a forge weld...</i>

06:58.918 --> 07:00.503
Hot steel!

07:00.503 --> 07:03.131
Because any impurities
can damage your weld

07:03.131 --> 07:05.592
and get you not to stick.

07:05.592 --> 07:09.638
My game plan is to get
my barbell flattened out

07:09.638 --> 07:12.098
and I got two pieces
of mild steel cut out

07:12.098 --> 07:14.100
and I'm gonna just go ahead
and stack 'em on there

07:14.100 --> 07:16.936
and forge weld 'em as fast
as I can and get it rocking.

07:16.936 --> 07:18.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:18.271 --> 07:20.649
‐ Wow, that's a thin
piece of steel.

07:20.649 --> 07:22.776
Keep in mind that he'll have to
grind the blade at some point.

07:22.776 --> 07:24.319
He'll have to be careful

07:24.319 --> 07:26.321
not to grind
all of that mild steel off.

07:26.321 --> 07:28.698
‐ In this particular challenge,

07:28.698 --> 07:31.451
chopping into one of those
45‐pound weights,

07:31.451 --> 07:34.120
it's gonna be
kind of critical

07:34.120 --> 07:36.623
that that blade
has some give and spring to it.

07:36.623 --> 07:40.043
‐ Yeah.
‐ And now we wait.

07:40.043 --> 07:42.212
<i>‐ I picked the steel</i>
<i>off the leg curl.</i>

07:42.212 --> 07:44.130
<i>It's a good piece</i>
<i>of hardenable steel.</i>

07:44.130 --> 07:46.132
Trying to get the blade
shaped out first,

07:46.132 --> 07:48.885
<i>then we'll add the secondary</i>
<i>piece into it.</i>

07:48.885 --> 07:51.137
<i>If my forge welding skills</i>
<i>was a little better,</i>

07:51.137 --> 07:54.307
I'd try a San Mai or a taco,
something like that.

07:54.307 --> 07:56.976
<i>I'm gonna try</i>
<i>and kind of play it safe,</i>

07:56.976 --> 07:58.353
put a little mild steel
in the handle

07:58.353 --> 07:59.979
<i>and hope for the best.</i>

07:59.979 --> 08:03.525
‐ Bladesmiths,
over 90 minutes has elapsed.

08:03.525 --> 08:06.653
You have one hour
and 23 minutes remaining

08:06.653 --> 08:08.988
to finish your work.

08:08.988 --> 08:12.367
‐ All right, Braxton's weld
looks pretty good.

08:12.367 --> 08:13.952
All Braxton has to do now

08:13.952 --> 08:16.329
