<i>this problem at home.</i>

11:30.273 --> 11:34.485
When you do multiple quenches,
you can get cracking.

11:34.485 --> 11:37.030
<i>Your welds will split.</i>

11:37.030 --> 11:39.490
You can get all sorts
of kinds of problems.

11:39.490 --> 11:41.701
‐ Yeah, if I were Braxton,
what I'd do is,

11:41.701 --> 11:43.036
I'd get some
of that angle iron,

11:43.036 --> 11:44.913
I'd put it in a vise,

11:44.913 --> 11:47.790
I'd do my quench and get it
in that vise and clamp it down

11:47.790 --> 11:51.377
so it cools the rest of the way
in a vise being held straight.

11:51.377 --> 11:53.087
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:53.087 --> 11:55.423
‐ Do you suppose he's going
for an edge quench?

11:55.423 --> 11:57.550
‐ That looks exactly
like what he's up to.

11:57.550 --> 11:59.219
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:59.219 --> 12:01.054
‐ I quench it again,
and I have the same problem.

12:01.054 --> 12:03.389
It's got a little warp
in the tang.

12:03.389 --> 12:05.642
Got hard.

12:05.642 --> 12:06.935
‐ Man!

12:06.935 --> 12:10.772
And Braxton is in back
in the forge, man.

12:10.772 --> 12:12.607
‐ I don't believe
that Braxton's blade

12:12.607 --> 12:16.027
was cold enough
to get hard.

12:16.027 --> 12:17.904
You really have to wait
'til the very end

12:17.904 --> 12:20.573
of that cooling cycle
for it to skate a file.

12:20.573 --> 12:22.659
‐ I'm not gonna move
onto the second round,

12:22.659 --> 12:25.662
pretty sure, if I can't get
this warp out. It's pretty bad.

12:25.662 --> 12:28.414
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:28.414 --> 12:30.416
<i>‐ I'm really liking</i>
<i>my rough grind,</i>

12:30.416 --> 12:33.336
so now I've got to get
this blade hard.

12:33.336 --> 12:37.048
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:37.048 --> 12:39.509
<i>There's no warp,</i>
<i>and I am really happy</i>

12:39.509 --> 12:42.595
<i>with the hardness</i>
<i>I got out of this blade.</i>

12:42.595 --> 12:45.598
I'm just having a blast.
This is‐‐this is awesome.

12:45.598 --> 12:47.767
‐ I'm going in for the quench
right now, man.

12:47.767 --> 12:51.062
My biggest concern at this
moment is picking up a warp,

12:51.062 --> 12:54.107
and I'm hoping I haven't
ground off all my mild steel.

12:54.107 --> 12:58.111
I'm pretty sure I haven't,
but we'll see.

12:58.111 --> 13:02.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:02.615 --> 13:04.200
I like it!

13:04.200 --> 13:07.829
‐ Jake's blade is maybe
one of the thinnest

13:07.829 --> 13:10.540
we've ever
had come out of a round one.

13:10.540 --> 13:12.792
‐ And narrow.

13:12.792 --> 13:15.295
‐ Five minutes!

13:15.295 --> 13:17.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:17.130 --> 13:18.464
‐ Yeah, boy.

13:18.464 --> 13:21.259
‐ It looks like Kyle
just quenched.

13:21.259 --> 13:23.136
‐ Yep.

13:23.136 --> 13:25.888
‐ It looks pretty straight.
‐ Looks pretty straight.

13:25.888 --> 13:29.392
‐ I think she's good.
‐ Braxton just quenched again.

13:29.392 --> 13:31.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:31.811 --> 13:33.813
‐ It's taken me four quenches
to get this blade

13:33.813 --> 13:36.482
to the straightness
that I want it.

13:36.482 --> 13:38.985
It's not as hard
as I would like it,

13:38.985 --> 13:40.570
but it's gonna have to work.

13:40.570 --> 13:43.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:43.990 --> 13:46.993
‐ Five, four, three,

13:46.993 --> 13:49.704
two, one.
Bladesmiths,

13:49.704 --> 13:51.664
shut down your machines,
drop your tools.

13:51.664 --> 13:55.168
This first round
of competition is over.

13:55.168 --> 13:58.671
[applause]

13:58.671 --> 14:01.299
<i>‐ I put my blade on my anvil</i>

14:01.299 --> 14:03.217
<i>and I start looking</i>
<i>at my competitors' blades</i>

14:03.217 --> 14:06.095
<i>and I'm hoping and praying</i>
<i>that my blade makes the cut.</i>

14:06.095 --> 14:07.638
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

14:07.638 --> 14:09.515
Now it's time for the judges
to take a look

14:09.515 --> 14:11.059
at what you've done
to that steel

14:11.059 --> 14:14.187
for the last three hours.
Jake, you're up first.

14:14.187 --> 14:16.022
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:16.022 --> 14:17.857
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:17.857 --> 14:19.901
<i>‐ Well, Jake, first thing</i>
<i>that strikes me</i>

14:19.901 --> 14:23.029
<i>on picking up this blade is,</i>
<i>it's really light and thin.</i>

14:23.029 --> 14:24.864
Might have liked to see it
be a little beefier

14:24.864 --> 14:26.365
for these kind of
of grueling tasks

14:26.365 --> 14:28.326
that we always put
these things through.

14:28.326 --> 14:30.703
Little bit of a warp
down near the tang,

14:30.703 --> 14:33.039
and I can see whispers
of weld lines.

14:33.039 --> 14:36.042
But aside from that,
nice, strong welds.

14:36.042 --> 14:37.794
It's got an interesting
chopper look to it.

14:37.794 --> 14:39.295
Nice job.
‐ Thank you.

14:39.295 --> 14:40.713
‐ All right, Braxton,
you're up.

14:40.713 --> 14:42.965
Please present
your blade to the judges.

14:42.965 --> 14:44.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:44.550 --> 14:46.385
<i>‐ Well, Braxton,</i>
<i>from the beginning,</i>

14:46.385 --> 14:48.888
<i>it was great</i>
<i>to watch you work out there,</i>

14:48.888 --> 14:50.348
but then when you went
to the quench,

14:50.348 --> 14:52.809
you got a warp
on your first one.

14:52.809 --> 14:54.227
Tried to fix that.
That's fine.

14:54.227 --> 14:55.603
On your second one,

14:55.603 --> 14:57.897
you have to wait
for the hardness to come,

14:57.897 --> 14:59.273
and if you're still
file checking

14:59.273 --> 15:00.900
when the thing is smoking,

15:00.900 --> 15:02.610
it hasn't had a chance
to do its thing yet.

15:02.610 --> 15:04.570
All that being said,
it's a really handsome knife.

15:04.570 --> 15:06.614
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

15:06.614 --> 15:08.407
‐ Are you ready for this, Kyle?

15:08.407 --> 15:09.742
‐ Ready or not.

15:09.742 --> 15:12.912
‐ Present your blade
to the judges.

15:12.912 --> 15:16.124
<i>‐ Well, Kyle, another good</i>
<i>competition chopper shape.</i>

15:16.124 --> 15:18.793
<i>You know, there's nothing</i>
<i>in this particular description</i>

15:18.793 --> 15:20.753
<i>or challenge that</i>
<i>would necessitate a point,</i>

15:20.753 --> 15:23.256
<i>so wise use of your metal.</i>

15:23.256 --> 15:24.632
If I remember right,

15:24.632 --> 15:25.925
the mild is all back here
in the tang.

15:25.925 --> 15:27.426
Is that right?
‐ Yes, sir.

15:27.426 --> 15:29.762
‐ I see a small delamination
on the weld here,

15:29.762 --> 15:33.015
but, you know, your blade
is really straight.

15:33.015 --> 15:35.893
It's got a nice weight to it.
Well done.

15:35.893 --> 15:37.770
‐ Thank you.
‐ Steve, you're up.

15:37.770 --> 15:39.605
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:39.605 --> 15:41.774
<i>‐ I really like the design</i>
<i>of your blade,</i>

15:41.774 --> 15:43.860
but something's wrong here.

15:43.860 --> 15:46.279
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.279 --> 15:49.323
Okay, Wil, the parameters were?

15:49.323 --> 15:51.784
‐ 11 to 14 inches,
no longer than 22

15:51.784 --> 15:53.369
at the end of the round.

15:53.369 --> 15:57.039
‐ Your cutting edge
is only maybe 10 1/2.

15:57.039 --> 15:58.499
‐ Wow.

15:58.499 --> 16:00.960
‐ So your blade's
a solid 1/2 inch short.

16:00.960 --> 16:02.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:02.795 --> 16:05.298
‐ Bladesmiths, the parameters
exist so that your blades

16:05.298 --> 16:09.302
can be measured evenly
and fairly against one another.

16:09.302 --> 16:11.304
Steve, your blade
failed to meet

16:11.304 --> 16:13.806
the 11‐ to 14‐inch parameter
by 1/2 an inch.

16:13.806 --> 16:15.433
That's grounds
for immediate dismissal,

16:15.433 --> 16:17.101
so at this time

16:17.101 --> 16:20.563
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

16:20.563 --> 16:22.398
<i>‐ I measured it</i>
<i>about 20 times,</i>

16:22.398 --> 16:23.983
<i>and I guess these old eyes</i>

16:23.983 --> 16:27.028
aren't as good
as those young bucks out there.

16:27.028 --> 16:30.156
Overall, it was a great time,
and I had a blast.

16:30.156 --> 16:33.159
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:33.159 --> 16:34.994
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

16:34.994 --> 16:36.829
You made it to the second
round of competition,

16:36.829 --> 16:38.664
and now it's time
to take those tempered blades

16:38.664 --> 16:42.835
and attach handles to them
in keeping with our gym theme.

16:42.835 --> 16:46.255
On the pantry shelves, we have
some weight belts and gym mats

16:46.255 --> 16:49.050
from which to make stacked
rubber and leather handles.

16:49.050 --> 16:51.928
You must also include guards
and pommels or butt caps

16:51.928 --> 16:53.888
to hold everything in place.

16:53.888 --> 16:55.514
You have three hours in which
to complete this challenge.

16:55.514 --> 16:57.391
At the end of this challenge,

16:57.391 --> 16:58.809
your blade will be tested
for strength and durability

16:58.809 --> 17:01.354
in that 45‐pound
weight plate chop

17:01.354 --> 17:03.606
and for edge retention
in the bag slice.

17:03.606 --> 17:05.107
After your blades
have been tested,

17:05.107 --> 17:06.901
one of you will have
to surrender your weapon

17:06.901 --> 17:10.363
and leave The Forge.
Your three hours starts now.

17:10.363 --> 17:12.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:12.031 --> 17:15.451
We've stocked the shelves
with leather weight belts

17:15.451 --> 17:17.036
and then also some
rubber matting

17:17.036 --> 17:18.412
that you would see at a gym.

17:18.412 --> 17:20.122
Is this great
for handle material?

17:20.122 --> 17:22.208
‐ I've had some rubber handled
knives before,

17:22.208 --> 17:23.918
and they were actually
grippy and good.

17:23.918 --> 17:25.211
‐ My plan to get through
this challenge

17:25.211 --> 17:27.421
is to work it
it step‐by‐step,

17:27.421 --> 17:30.383
<i>guard, leather, rubber,</i>
<i>and butt cap.</i>

17:30.383 --> 17:33.886
<i>It's a trial‐and‐error thing</i>
<i>to set up a guard this way,</i>

17:33.886 --> 17:35.930
<i>so we're gonna see</i>
<i>how it goes.</i>

17:35.930 --> 17:37.640
‐ Braxton's working on a guard.

17:37.640 --> 17:39.725
Honestly, I think that's
the best way to start,

17:39.725 --> 17:41.060
'cause then you're gonna know

17:41.060 --> 17:43.229
how much handle material
you need.

17:43.229 --> 17:46.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:46.107 --> 17:48.734
<i>‐ Before I do anything else,</i>
<i>I want to make sure</i>

17:48.734 --> 17:50.236
<i>I can get a handle put on it.</i>

17:50.236 --> 17:52.071
You know,
other than blade breakage,

17:52.071 --> 17:54.907
probably handles are probably
pretty high on, you know,

17:54.907 --> 17:57.368
elimination reasons.

17:57.368 --> 17:59.120
<i>Probably just gonna go</i>
<i>leather, rubber,</i>

17:59.120 --> 18:01.289
<i>leather, rubber,</i>
<i>and stack it up.</i>

18:01.289 --> 18:03.416
Being as the belts
already have a hole in 'em,

18:03.416 --> 18:05.084
<i>I just need to add to it</i>
<i>just a little bit,</i>

18:05.084 --> 18:06.294
<i>make it where</i>
<i>it'll slide on there</i>

18:06.294 --> 18:07.837
<i>and kind of save me some time.</i>

18:07.837 --> 18:09.922
Basic rule, you know,
mechanicing

18:09.922 --> 18:12.258
and a lot of things
is the KISS emblem:

18:12.258 --> 18:14.677
Keep It Simple, Stupid.

18:14.677 --> 18:16.762
<i>‐ I decided to take out</i>
<i>the slight warp</i>

18:16.762 --> 18:18.598
<i>that the judges had mentioned,</i>

18:18.598 --> 18:20.891
and I'm also trying to make
the blade spine more durable,

18:20.891 --> 18:24.020
<i>'cause this chopping test</i>
<i>is gonna be serious business.</i>

18:24.020 --> 18:27.106
I'm gonna keep my edge cold
in some water and/or oil

18:27.106 --> 18:30.192
and just do a light temper
across the back of the spine.

18:30.192 --> 18:32.278
‐ Jake has
to be very careful about

18:32.278 --> 18:34.071
the blue back that he's doing

18:34.071 --> 18:36.657
because he's got
a very thin blade already.

18:36.657 --> 18:38.951
When he hits the metal plates
with that edge at the end,

18:38.951 --> 18:41.287
that's gonna really dull it.

18:41.287 --> 18:43.748
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

18:43.748 --> 18:46.375
You have two hours remaining
to finish those handles.

18:46.375 --> 18:47.668
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:47.668 --> 18:49.170
‐ I get all my pieces cut,

18:49.170 --> 18:52.048
<i>take 'em over</i>
<i>to the drill press.</i>

18:52.048 --> 18:54.008
<i>The leather is clogging</i>
<i>the drill bit.</i>

18:54.008 --> 18:56.510
<i>It's not going</i>
<i>all the way through.</i>

18:56.510 --> 18:58.179
<i>I'm freaking out a little bit.</i>

18:58.179 --> 18:59.805
‐ The leather we have
on these belts

18:59.805 --> 19:01.307
are thicker than normal.

19:01.307 --> 19:03.309
‐ Yeah, it's doubled up.
It's two or three layers.

19:03.309 --> 19:04.977
<i>‐ Using the Dremel</i>
<i>on the rubber,</i>

19:04.977 --> 19:06.729
<i>it's wanting</i>
<i>to clog up and burn.</i>

19:06.729 --> 19:08.481
<i>It's not really wanting</i>
<i>to cut through it,</i>

19:08.481 --> 19:11.817
so I go over to the pantry
and I grab a chisel

19:11.817 --> 19:14.695
<i>and hammer</i>
<i>the little section out</i>

19:14.695 --> 19:17.823
<i>in between the two holes,</i>
<i>and that worked out great.</i>

19:17.823 --> 19:19.033
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:19.033 --> 19:20.660
<i>‐ My guard's got to fit well.</i>

19:20.660 --> 19:22.495
You know, one,
protect the hand,

19:22.495 --> 19:25.247
<i>two, it's got to hold</i>
<i>all the material together</i>

19:25.247 --> 19:28.000
<i>and hold everything tight.</i>

19:28.000 --> 19:30.002
I couldn't find a piece
of brass that I wanted.

19:30.002 --> 19:31.837
We're gonna use some G10.

19:31.837 --> 19:33.506
‐ There you go.
‐ The end of the tang

19:33.506 --> 19:35.758
is gonna have to be thinner
than the middle part,

19:35.758 --> 19:37.176
or even up here, you know,

19:37.176 --> 19:39.136
so that way,
the guard will fit.

19:39.136 --> 19:41.555
Rubber, leather, and all of it
will fit like it's supposed to.

19:41.555 --> 19:45.267
<i>My mild steel is on my tang.</i>
<i>Even if it does have a delam,</i>

19:45.267 --> 19:48.229
you know, it'll be hidden
once I get a handle put on it.

19:48.229 --> 19:50.022
‐ One thing about these
stacked handles,

19:50.022 --> 19:52.692
especially these ones
with the rubber layers,

19:52.692 --> 19:54.944
they're not a lot of support.
They're not like

19:54.944 --> 19:56.737
a piece of wood
that's around the outside.

19:56.737 --> 19:59.198
‐ So there's no opportunity
to really reinforce

19:59.198 --> 20:00.700
the structural integrity

20:00.700 --> 20:02.702
of your tang
with your handle material

20:02.702 --> 20:04.704
when you're doing stacked
rubber and leather.

20:04.704 --> 20:07.707
‐ Yeah.
‐ So a tang imperfection,

20:07.707 --> 20:10.876
like the one that we saw
in Kyle's blade,

20:10.876 --> 20:13.379
it is not fully protected
from a potential break.

20:13.379 --> 20:15.756
‐ That's true.

20:15.756 --> 20:18.926
<i>‐ After I finish doing</i>
<i>my tempering of the blade,</i>

20:18.926 --> 20:21.554
my game plan is to get
one of those mild steel pipes

20:21.554 --> 20:24.223
out of the bucket in the back

20:24.223 --> 20:26.726
<i>and then put a sharp edge</i>
<i>on it and use it as a punch</i>

20:26.726 --> 20:29.228
<i>to punch out the leather</i>
<i>and the rubber.</i>

20:29.228 --> 20:31.397
I start wailing on it,
and I just notice

20:31.397 --> 20:33.274
<i>that it's not cutting</i>
<i>all the way through,</i>

20:33.274 --> 20:35.568
<i>and I am extremely frustrated,</i>

20:35.568 --> 20:38.237
<i>because I'm spending too much</i>
<i>time trying to mess with this,</i>

20:38.237 --> 20:42.450
so I decide to go for a plan B
and try and use the press

20:42.450 --> 20:45.870
<i>to punch out</i>
<i>all of my leather pieces.</i>

20:45.870 --> 20:48.038
‐ What‐‐Jake's doing
a lot of work

20:48.038 --> 20:50.291
and maybe not
the best time management.

20:50.291 --> 20:51.917
<i>‐ I'm really trying</i>
<i>to calm my nerve,</i>

20:51.917 --> 20:53.753
but this is a whole
'nother animal,

20:53.753 --> 20:56.088
and that clock
never stops ticking.

20:56.088 --> 20:59.467
‐ Bladesmiths,
2 1/2 hours has elapsed.

20:59.467 --> 21:01.969
You only have
30 minutes remaining.

21:01.969 --> 21:03.763
<i>‐ It's not working</i>
<i>the way I want,</i>

21:03.763 --> 21:05.514
<i>so I'm getting</i>
<i>extremely frustrated.</i>

21:05.514 --> 21:06.891
<i>I feel like an amateur.</i>

21:06.891 --> 21:08.100
I'm letting the pressure
get to me,

21:08.100 --> 21:09.643
which is not my way at all,

21:09.643 --> 21:11.604
<i>but I realize</i>
<i>that I am really behind.</i>

21:14.899 --> 21:16.233
‐ You know,
it's good initiative,

21:16.233 --> 21:17.902
but I wonder
if the cookie cutter

21:17.902 --> 21:18.944
isn't more trouble
than it's worth.

21:18.944 --> 21:20.696
<i>‐ I'm at a loss.</i>

21:20.696 --> 21:22.531
<i>So then I finally decide</i>
<i>to scrap this idea.</i>

21:22.531 --> 21:24.325
I'm gonna have to
cut 'em out square, dude.

21:24.325 --> 21:27.661
<i>And I'm just gonna chop it up</i>
<i>in the band saw.</i>

21:27.661 --> 21:32.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:32.041 --> 21:34.168
<i>‐ After I get</i>
<i>my handle peened,</i>

21:34.168 --> 21:35.836
I go to the grinder

21:35.836 --> 21:40.216
<i>and I start hogging</i>
<i>leather and rubber off.</i>

21:40.216 --> 21:41.926
‐ Braxton is really making
short work

21:41.926 --> 21:43.803
of shaping that handle.
‐ That's just it.

21:43.803 --> 21:46.764
The risk is to actually grind
too much material away

21:46.764 --> 21:48.766
because he's moving
so quickly.

21:48.766 --> 21:52.061
‐ As I'm grinding on my handle,
I grind too far.

21:52.061 --> 21:53.729
Just sharpened my blade.

21:53.729 --> 21:56.607
I got one little spot
on the handle to fix.

21:56.607 --> 21:58.567
Got a little hole in it.

21:58.567 --> 22:00.653
It won't come out,
but it just doesn't look good.

22:00.653 --> 22:03.447
‐ Braxton's got to be a little
bit disappointed with himself.

22:03.447 --> 22:05.533
Now he's got that little gap.

22:05.533 --> 22:07.034
Would that be
driving you crazy?

22:07.034 --> 22:08.244
‐ Yeah, of course.

22:08.244 --> 22:10.412
<i>‐ I just go and fill that in</i>

22:10.412 --> 22:13.415
<i>with a little bit of superglue</i>
<i>and a little piece of leather,</i>

22:13.415 --> 22:18.254
<i>and I press on it and</i>
<i>press on it, and it's hard.</i>

22:18.254 --> 22:21.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:21.257 --> 22:24.677
‐ It's a good idea to contact
cement each of the layers,

22:24.677 --> 22:26.387
'cause you're gonna make
an oval or something like that,

22:26.387 --> 22:28.347
and if it's not compressed
really, really well,

22:28.347 --> 22:32.101
you get
a little rotation in use.

22:32.101 --> 22:33.727
‐ My game plan right now
with the pommel

22:33.727 --> 22:35.729
is just a piece of mild steel
and weld it on.

22:35.729 --> 22:37.731
<i>I'm a pretty good welder,</i>
<i>so I felt like</i>

22:37.731 --> 22:40.943
<i>that was probably</i>
<i>the best route for me.</i>

22:40.943 --> 22:43.445
<i>‐ I drilled a hole in</i>
<i>the pommel, and I get it fit.</i>

22:43.445 --> 22:45.155
I can go ahead
and peen it down.

22:45.155 --> 22:47.616
‐ Jake has decided that
that little bit of peening

22:47.616 --> 22:49.326
is gonna hold
everything into place.

22:49.326 --> 22:51.412
‐ To be honest, if it's
a tight fit in the hole,

22:51.412 --> 22:53.998
it doesn't take much extra

22:53.998 --> 22:56.709
to make it really hard
to pull through that hole.

22:56.709 --> 22:58.502
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths.

22:58.502 --> 23:02.006
Only five minutes remaining
in this round.

23:02.006 --> 23:03.716
<i>‐ I still need to put an edge</i>
<i>on this thing,</i>

23:03.716 --> 23:05.509
<i>so I'm pretty stressed</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

23:05.509 --> 23:07.344
I realize
that I am really behind.

23:07.344 --> 23:09.763
My only hope is for one
of y'all to [bleep] up.

23:09.763 --> 23:11.223
‐ Don't quit, man.

23:11.223 --> 23:13.976
It ain't over
until the fat lady sings.

23:13.976 --> 23:16.937
‐ Five, four, three,

23:16.937 --> 23:19.189
two, one.

23:19.189 --> 23:21.942
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.
This second round

23:21.942 --> 23:24.778
of bladesmithing
competition is over.

23:24.778 --> 23:27.740
<i>‐ I feel like I have a chance</i>
<i>in the test,</i>

23:27.740 --> 23:29.950
but, you know,
it's any man's game out there.

23:29.950 --> 23:32.745
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:32.745 --> 23:33.996
‐ Bladesmiths,
to test the strength

23:33.996 --> 23:35.748
and durability of your blades

23:35.748 --> 23:37.458
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

23:37.458 --> 23:39.126
I'll be batoning them
mercilessly

23:39.126 --> 23:41.545
into this weight plate.
Remember,

23:41.545 --> 23:43.631
this test is all about what
the plate does to your knives

23:43.631 --> 23:46.634
and not what your knives
do to the plate.

23:46.634 --> 23:48.844
Braxton, you're up first.
Are you ready for this?

23:48.844 --> 23:51.388
‐ I feel a little nervous,
but go ahead.

23:51.388 --> 23:53.349
‐ All right.

23:53.349 --> 23:57.019
<i>‐ That is a piece of metal</i>
<i>they're gonna be hitting.</i>

23:57.019 --> 23:59.605
My blade didn't get as hard
as I wanted it to,

23:59.605 --> 24:01.398
so I'm starting to cringe.

24:01.398 --> 24:04.360
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

24:04.360 --> 24:11.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:18.457 --> 24:21.043
‐ Good job, man.
‐ Yeah.

24:21.043 --> 24:23.003
‐ Well, Braxton,
first things first,

24:23.003 --> 24:26.340
you can see where I hit
those weight plates.

24:26.340 --> 24:30.636
The first area is still sharp
but bent over.

24:30.636 --> 24:34.640
The second two areas
have significant rolling.

24:34.640 --> 24:37.977
That being said, the rest
of your knife is very sharp.

24:37.977 --> 24:39.645
Extremely
attractive‐looking knife.

24:39.645 --> 24:41.230
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

24:41.230 --> 24:43.732
‐ Kyle, you're up next.
What are you thinking?

24:43.732 --> 24:46.360
‐ Let her eat.
‐ All right.

24:46.360 --> 24:48.821
<i>‐ I am pretty sure my blade</i>
<i>can handle it, you know?</i>

24:48.821 --> 24:50.447
<i>I made it pretty thick,</i>
<i>pretty robust</i>

24:50.447 --> 24:52.324
<i>to handle that kind of abuse,</i>

24:52.324 --> 24:54.576
but it's hard
not to be concerned

24:54.576 --> 24:58.038
when they're gonna bash it
into a cast‐iron plate.

24:58.038 --> 25:02.793
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:02.793 --> 25:04.211
What the hell was that?

25:08.173 --> 25:11.343
‐ Kyle.

25:11.343 --> 25:13.721
‐ [bleep], it broke.

25:13.721 --> 25:17.850
‐ Your tang snapped in half.
It's at a very critical spot.

25:17.850 --> 25:20.019
We can't hold onto this
for further testing.

25:20.019 --> 25:22.438
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:22.438 --> 25:25.524
‐ It broke in the handle where
I forge‐welded that mild steel.

25:25.524 --> 25:28.193
‐ Kyle, your blade has suffered
a catastrophic failure

25:28.193 --> 25:30.029
in the handle
on the second strike.

25:30.029 --> 25:33.532
However, you're not out
of this competition just yet.

25:33.532 --> 25:36.326
Jake, that means that
your blade needs to survive

25:36.326 --> 25:39.246
two licks against that plate.
How are you feeling right now?

25:39.246 --> 25:42.541
‐ Um, pretty nervous.
‐ All right, gentlemen.

25:42.541 --> 25:45.210
Let's see what happens.
Ben?

25:45.210 --> 25:47.546
<i>‐ I know that my blade's</i>
<i>gonna be pretty durable,</i>

25:47.546 --> 25:49.214
<i>but my edge is pretty thin.</i>

25:49.214 --> 25:51.633
<i>I'm hoping that mine</i>
<i>can outperform his,</i>

25:51.633 --> 25:53.677
<i>because at this point,</i>
<i>it's my only hope.</i>

25:53.677 --> 25:55.387
‐ It'll make it.

25:55.387 --> 25:58.307
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:58.307 --> 26:00.059
One more.

26:00.059 --> 26:03.937
‐ As Ben goes to make
the second strike on my blade,

26:03.937 --> 26:06.148
<i>it's all</i>
<i>in slow‐motion for me.</i>

26:06.148 --> 26:07.316
<i>My heart is in my throat.</i>

26:07.316 --> 26:14.323
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:15.282 --> 26:16.492
‐ There you go.

26:16.492 --> 26:18.077
‐ [sighs]

26:18.077 --> 26:20.204
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:20.204 --> 26:23.207
‐ Jake, congratulations.
Your blade held up.

26:23.207 --> 26:24.792
Kyle, because your weapon

26:24.792 --> 26:26.919
suffered a catastrophic failure
in the handle

26:26.919 --> 26:28.754
and can no longer
continue in testing,

26:28.754 --> 26:31.006
I have to eliminate you
from this competition.

26:31.006 --> 26:32.800
‐ Hey, man,
it was a pleasure.

26:32.800 --> 26:35.094
<i>Blades are only as strong</i>
<i>as their weakest point,</i>

26:35.094 --> 26:38.305
and mine was in the handle.

26:38.305 --> 26:40.349
I may not be the
"Forged in Fire" champion,

26:40.349 --> 26:44.186
but finishing a blade
and being here was awesome.

26:44.186 --> 26:45.604
<i>Definitely do it again</i>
<i>in a heartbeat.</i>

26:45.604 --> 26:49.149
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:49.149 --> 26:50.526
‐ Braxton, Jake,
congratulations.

26:50.526 --> 26:52.111
You fellas have made it

26:52.111 --> 26:53.612
to the third round
of this competition.

26:53.612 --> 26:55.572
Now we're sending you
back to your home forges

26:55.572 --> 26:57.699
to make this iconic weapon
from history...

26:57.699 --> 27:01.286
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:01.286 --> 27:04.123
The nagamaki.

27:04.123 --> 27:06.333
‐ [sighs]

27:06.333 --> 27:08.961
<i>‐ Reaching its peak use</i>
<i>during the Muromachi era,</i>

27:08.961 --> 27:11.171
<i>the nagamaki was</i>
<i>a long, two‐handed weapon</i>

27:11.171 --> 27:13.674
<i>that assisted samurai warriors</i>
<i>in feudal Japan</i>

27:13.674 --> 27:15.676
<i>for over four centuries.</i>

27:15.676 --> 27:18.178
<i>Its slightly curved blade</i>
<i>nearing 30 inches in length</i>

27:18.178 --> 27:20.681
<i>and equally long handle</i>
<i>gave the user</i>

27:20.681 --> 27:24.142
<i>complete, precise control,</i>
<i>making it a highly effective</i>

27:24.142 --> 27:25.978
<i>and lethal slicing weapon</i>

27:25.978 --> 27:29.147
<i>ideal for infantry warriors</i>
<i>combating horsemen.</i>

27:29.147 --> 27:30.899
<i>Traditional Japanese swords</i>
<i>have had</i>

27:30.899 --> 27:33.652
<i>a long‐standing influence</i>
<i>on pop culture weaponry,</i>

27:33.652 --> 27:36.238
<i>especially in fantasy films</i>
<i>like "Lord of the Rings,"</i>

27:36.238 --> 27:38.156
<i>where the Elvish lhang</i>
<i>shares a similar</i>

27:38.156 --> 27:40.659
<i>hilt and blade construction</i>
<i>as the nagamaki.</i>

27:40.659 --> 27:41.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:41.869 --> 27:43.871
Bladesmiths, your nagamaki

27:43.871 --> 27:45.831
must fall within
the following parameters:

27:45.831 --> 27:47.499
the length of your blade
must be between

27:47.499 --> 27:50.168
31 and 33 inches in length.

27:50.168 --> 27:52.212
It must be single‐edged.

27:52.212 --> 27:55.173
It must be at least an inch
and a half wide at the habaki

27:55.173 --> 27:56.675
and tapered to that tip.

27:56.675 --> 27:58.552
You must have
a tsuba‐style guard

27:58.552 --> 28:01.096
and a traditional wrap
on the handle.

28:01.096 --> 28:04.558
‐ Nagamaki, it's a‐‐
that's a new word for me.

28:04.558 --> 28:06.059
[laughs]

28:06.059 --> 28:08.395
<i>I've never done</i>
<i>a Japanese‐style weapon.</i>

28:08.395 --> 28:11.690
Never made a habaki.
Never made a tsuba‐style guard

28:11.690 --> 28:14.735
or anything like that.
It's gonna be interesting.

28:14.735 --> 28:16.320
‐ We'll be sending you back
to your home forges,

28:16.320 --> 28:18.363
but this time,
we're taking it up a notch.

28:18.363 --> 28:20.407
You'll only have four days
in your home forges

28:20.407 --> 28:22.034
to complete your work,

28:22.034 --> 28:23.869
and at the end of those
four days, you'll return

28:23.869 --> 28:26.246
and present your weapons
to our expert judges.

28:26.246 --> 28:28.248
After they've tested them,

28:28.248 --> 28:29.917
they'll declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

28:29.917 --> 28:33.295
and you'll leave here
with a check for 10 grand.

28:33.295 --> 28:35.964
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

28:35.964 --> 28:42.763
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:42.763 --> 28:46.224
<i>‐ It's day one.</i>
<i>I'm back at the home forge.</i>

28:46.224 --> 28:47.893
I'm pretty nervous.

28:47.893 --> 28:51.396
<i>Going to make</i>
<i>my first Japanese sword.</i>

28:51.396 --> 28:53.398
<i>I think the biggest challenge</i>
<i>is gonna be</i>

28:53.398 --> 28:55.776
the length of the nagamaki.

28:55.776 --> 28:58.111
<i>It's longer than anything</i>
<i>I've ever made before,</i>

28:58.111 --> 29:01.990
and it's gonna be hard
to keep all that straight.

29:01.990 --> 29:04.910
<i>The first thing I do</i>
<i>is taking it down to size.</i>

29:04.910 --> 29:06.912
[machine whirring]

29:06.912 --> 29:10.123
<i>Straightening this blade</i>
<i>is a hassle.</i>

29:10.123 --> 29:12.084
<i>It's wanting to curve</i>
<i>like a banana,</i>

29:12.084 --> 29:16.129
and I'm having to straighten it
out little by little.

29:16.129 --> 29:20.676
I have to be very meticulous
on the amount of curve it has.

29:20.676 --> 29:27.683
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:30.435 --> 29:32.562
‐ It's day one back
at the forge here in Conroe,

29:32.562 --> 29:34.648
and I'm just really excited
to get started with this build,

29:34.648 --> 29:37.776
<i>but I've never made anything</i>
<i>to this magnitude, this big,</i>

29:37.776 --> 29:39.194
so it's gonna be a challenge.

29:39.194 --> 29:41.196
Yee‐haw, baby!

29:41.196 --> 29:43.782
<i>While I was in the Air Force,</i>
<i>I lived in Okinawa, Japan,</i>

29:43.782 --> 29:46.159
and I got to see a lot
of the history of the samurai,

29:46.159 --> 29:49.287
<i>so I've always wanted</i>
<i>to make a Japanese katana</i>

29:49.287 --> 29:52.040
or a blade of that nature.

29:52.040 --> 29:54.126
Well, that'll do.

29:54.126 --> 29:55.836
<i>The W2 that I have is already</i>

29:55.836 --> 29:57.921
<i>pretty close to the parameters</i>
<i>that I need,</i>

29:57.921 --> 30:00.716
<i>so I really don't have</i>
<i>to draw it out that much.</i>

30:00.716 --> 30:02.843
I've got the blade
pretty much forged out.

30:02.843 --> 30:04.761
<i>It's a little thinner</i>
<i>than I wanted,</i>

30:04.761 --> 30:06.471
<i>but as long as I get</i>
<i>a good heat treat tomorrow</i>

30:06.471 --> 30:08.223
<i>and it's nice and hard,</i>

30:08.223 --> 30:09.850
<i>it'll have</i>
<i>a little bit of flex to it.</i>

30:09.850 --> 30:13.145
That's a [bleep]ing
straight blade right there.

30:13.145 --> 30:14.479
Hell yeah!

30:14.479 --> 30:18.316
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:18.316 --> 30:20.652
<i>‐ I feel like I got</i>
<i>a pretty good, sound blade,</i>

30:20.652 --> 30:23.321
but we won't know anything
until after the quench.

30:23.321 --> 30:30.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:31.705 --> 30:34.249
<i>The blade takes a warp.</i>

30:34.249 --> 30:36.835
Oh, man.
That's not good.

30:36.835 --> 30:38.712
It actually straightened
the blade out.

30:38.712 --> 30:40.839
<i>That made it to where</i>
<i>I was under parameters</i>

30:40.839 --> 30:43.050
for the minimum bend
in the blade.

30:43.050 --> 30:45.719
<i>I have to heat it back up,</i>
<i>put a bend back in it,</i>

30:45.719 --> 30:50.265
<i>and requench.</i>
<i>I'm freaking out a little bit.</i>

30:50.265 --> 30:52.517
Try this again.

30:52.517 --> 30:57.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:57.439 --> 31:00.692
As I do my second quench,
I pull my blade out,

31:00.692 --> 31:04.071
and it has
the bend requirements now,

31:04.071 --> 31:05.864
<i>so it worked out.</i>

31:05.864 --> 31:09.034
Oh, it's just there.

31:09.034 --> 31:11.870
I'm just relieved.

31:11.870 --> 31:13.455
It's hard.

31:13.455 --> 31:16.374
It's time to start thinking
about the habaki.

31:16.374 --> 31:21.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:21.630 --> 31:25.050
<i>For the most part,</i>
<i>the habaki is stuck together.</i>

31:25.050 --> 31:28.637
<i>It's uglier than sin,</i>
<i>but this competition, I think,</i>

31:28.637 --> 31:31.723
mainly, it's about function
more than pretty.

31:31.723 --> 31:32.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:32.891 --> 31:35.060
I'm glad today's over.

31:35.060 --> 31:38.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:38.897 --> 31:40.816
‐ It's the start of day two,
and I'm ready to get to work

31:40.816 --> 31:42.400
and try to get
this blade quenched.

31:42.400 --> 31:44.027
Fire 'em up and get 'em hot.

31:44.027 --> 31:45.445
<i>I've never wielded</i>
<i>anything that big,</i>

31:45.445 --> 31:47.447
and I really just
can't wait to test it.

31:47.447 --> 31:48.907
I can't wait to swing
that thing around in the yard

31:48.907 --> 31:50.408
just to have a feel
for how it is.

31:50.408 --> 31:56.790
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:56.790 --> 31:59.584
I check the blade,
and it's hard, it's straight,

31:59.584 --> 32:02.170
and I just have
such a sense of relief.

32:02.170 --> 32:05.257
Let's hack at something,
see if it's gonna break.

32:05.257 --> 32:06.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:06.800 --> 32:07.801
[bleep].

32:11.555 --> 32:14.683
<i>It snapped the tip off about</i>
<i>six inches down from the tip.</i>

32:14.683 --> 32:16.977
<i>I will not be able to meet</i>
<i>parameters with this blade,</i>

32:16.977 --> 32:19.729
so I decide
to start a new blade.

32:19.729 --> 32:21.314
Son of a bitch.

32:21.314 --> 32:22.774
You know, it probably
had a stress fracture.

32:22.774 --> 32:25.026
The grain in there
is pretty tight.

32:25.026 --> 32:26.695
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:26.695 --> 32:28.363
I got half a day left
to hammer out

32:28.363 --> 32:30.866
and forge out a blade.
[bleep].

32:30.866 --> 32:32.409
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:32.409 --> 32:34.661
<i>‐ Now that I've got</i>
<i>the blade done,</i>

32:34.661 --> 32:36.204
<i>we've got the habaki done,</i>

32:36.204 --> 32:38.165
and now it's time
to do the tsuba.

32:38.165 --> 32:39.749
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:39.749 --> 32:41.168
<i>The guard is very important.</i>

32:41.168 --> 32:42.669
<i>Everything needs to be smooth.</i>

32:42.669 --> 32:45.881
Oh, that's a tight fit.
Feels really good.

32:45.881 --> 32:47.841
It's just a little bit heavy.

32:47.841 --> 32:51.261
The nagamaki being too heavy
can make it unwieldable

32:51.261 --> 32:54.598
and make it uncomfortable
to swing around.

32:54.598 --> 32:57.142
Right where that guard is,
it's a little heavy.

32:57.142 --> 33:00.896
<i>I mill a simple pattern into</i>
<i>the tsuba to lose some weight.</i>

33:00.896 --> 33:03.982
That actually feels
a lot better now.

33:03.982 --> 33:05.192
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:05.192 --> 33:06.902
<i>All I lack is the wrapping</i>

33:06.902 --> 33:08.695
<i>and doing a final cleanup.</i>

33:08.695 --> 33:11.740
<i>I only have a few little</i>
<i>things to do on day four.</i>

33:11.740 --> 33:12.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:12.991 --> 33:14.910
This is cool.

33:14.910 --> 33:16.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:16.912 --> 33:18.330
<i>‐ My last day,</i>
<i>I have so much to do,</i>

33:18.330 --> 33:20.624
<i>I have no room for error.</i>

33:20.624 --> 33:22.709
I was able
to forge out a blade,

33:22.709 --> 33:24.377
grind it out,
and get it quenched,

33:24.377 --> 33:27.172
so I'm just gonna try
and meet the parameters

33:27.172 --> 33:29.549
<i>and get the blade</i>
<i>turned in and sharp.</i>

33:29.549 --> 33:30.759
That's pretty good.

33:30.759 --> 33:32.636
<i>I have my habaki done.</i>

33:32.636 --> 33:34.429
<i>That took me</i>
<i>a long time yesterday.</i>

33:34.429 --> 33:37.265
<i>I have my tsuba pretty much</i>
<i>the way I want it.</i>

33:37.265 --> 33:39.059
<i>My main goal for today</i>
<i>in general</i>

33:39.059 --> 33:40.936
<i>is just to get</i>
<i>the handle complete.</i>

33:40.936 --> 33:42.687
<i>I am quickly</i>
<i>running out of time.</i>

33:42.687 --> 33:44.773
<i>I need to make this handle</i>

33:44.773 --> 33:47.609
<i>as quickly and</i>
<i>as efficiently as possible.</i>

33:47.609 --> 33:49.236
<i>I'm trying to get</i>
<i>a pretty good grip</i>

33:49.236 --> 33:51.613
<i>to where the blade</i>
<i>is very easily indexed.</i>

33:51.613 --> 33:53.573
I don't want the handle
to be too thick,

33:53.573 --> 33:55.742
but, honestly, I just need
to get a handle on it.

33:55.742 --> 33:57.535
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:57.535 --> 33:59.955
Solid, that's for sure.

33:59.955 --> 34:02.082
<i>Once the glue dries</i>
<i>on the leather wrap,</i>

34:02.082 --> 34:06.336
I go ahead and start this
long process of the ito wrap.

34:06.336 --> 34:08.338
<i>This just so happens to be</i>
<i>one of the hardest builds</i>

34:08.338 --> 34:09.756
<i>I've ever done.</i>

34:09.756 --> 34:11.174
I really could've used
an extra day,

34:11.174 --> 34:13.468
<i>but I'm just happy</i>
<i>that it's over.</i>

34:13.468 --> 34:14.636
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:14.636 --> 34:16.680
Oh, that is smooth!

34:16.680 --> 34:19.641
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

34:19.641 --> 34:21.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:21.851 --> 34:23.979
‐ Braxton, Jake,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:23.979 --> 34:26.523
You fellas have had four days
at your home forges

34:26.523 --> 34:28.233
to work on your nagamakis.

34:28.233 --> 34:29.526
Braxton, how did it go?

34:29.526 --> 34:30.860
‐ It went pretty well.

34:30.860 --> 34:33.280
<i>My blade is forged from 5160,</i>

34:33.280 --> 34:35.991
<i>copper habaki,</i>
<i>mild steel guard.</i>

34:35.991 --> 34:39.494
<i>Used white ash for the handle</i>
<i>with the wrap over it.</i>

34:39.494 --> 34:41.079
‐ Jake, how'd it go for you?

34:41.079 --> 34:42.580
‐ It went pretty well.
That's blade number two.

34:42.580 --> 34:45.000
I made the second one
out of 1095.

34:45.000 --> 34:48.086
<i>My habaki and tsuba</i>
<i>are made of mokume‐gane</i>

34:48.086 --> 34:51.464
<i>and traditional ito wrap.</i>

34:51.464 --> 34:55.635
‐ Both of your weapons look
like imposing large swords,

34:55.635 --> 34:57.512
but are they gonna hold up
in our weapons test?

34:57.512 --> 34:58.888
That remains to be seen.

34:58.888 --> 35:00.974
We have a strength test,
a sharpness test,

35:00.974 --> 35:03.643
and up first, the KEAL test.
Doug?

35:03.643 --> 35:06.605
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:06.605 --> 35:08.148
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

35:08.148 --> 35:10.233
to find out how lethal
your nagamakis are,

35:10.233 --> 35:12.402
I will take your weapons
and deliver killing blows,

35:12.402 --> 35:15.947
slashes, and thrusts,
on this wild boar carcass.

35:15.947 --> 35:17.574
Braxton, you're up first.
You ready for this?

35:17.574 --> 35:20.744
‐ I'm ready. Go ahead.
‐ Let's do this.

35:20.744 --> 35:23.204
<i>‐ Oh, man, we have hogs</i>
<i>around where I'm from.</i>

35:23.204 --> 35:24.956
<i>Skin is very, very thick.</i>

35:24.956 --> 35:28.209
I'm nervous,
but there's nothing I can do.

35:28.209 --> 35:30.337
I just got to let the chips
fall where they lay.

35:30.337 --> 35:32.922
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.922 --> 35:35.967
‐ [grunting]

35:35.967 --> 35:42.974
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:45.435 --> 35:47.187
‐ [chuckles]

35:47.187 --> 35:49.272
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:49.272 --> 35:50.940
‐ All right, Braxton.

35:50.940 --> 35:55.528
Your nagamaki here
is definitely not boring.

35:55.528 --> 35:57.155
It is razor‐sharp.

35:57.155 --> 36:00.575
Every cut with this thick
wild boar carcass

36:00.575 --> 36:01.951
allowed me to peel off

36:01.951 --> 36:04.579
layers of the very thick
hide that it has.

36:04.579 --> 36:08.500
Also the lightness
that you have with this blade

36:08.500 --> 36:10.710
allows for switching
with the grip here.

36:10.710 --> 36:12.629
It's got very good grip
in the handle.

36:12.629 --> 36:15.590
I can index exactly where
the edge is at all times.

36:15.590 --> 36:19.636
Overall, sir,
your nagamaki will KEAL.

36:19.636 --> 36:21.054
‐ Thank you.

36:21.054 --> 36:23.348
‐ All right, Jake,
it's your turn.

36:23.348 --> 36:24.599
Ready for this?

36:24.599 --> 36:26.768
‐ Chop 'em up.
‐ Let's do this.

36:26.768 --> 36:28.645
<i>‐ It makes me</i>
<i>a little bit nervous.</i>

36:28.645 --> 36:30.814
<i>I really want mine to chop</i>
<i>through the boar as well,</i>

36:30.814 --> 36:33.483
but the blade can actually
take a lot of damage

36:33.483 --> 36:37.237
<i>during the boar testing</i>
<i>because there's bones.</i>

36:37.237 --> 36:39.989
<i>I know that Braxton's blade</i>
<i>set a very high bar</i>

36:39.989 --> 36:42.158
<i>and mine needs to perform</i>
<i>just as good as his.</i>

36:56.548 --> 37:03.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:06.057 --> 37:08.059
‐ All right, Jake, let's talk
about your nagamaki here.

37:08.059 --> 37:09.602
It's sharp.

37:09.602 --> 37:12.731
Wielding this weapon
is a lot of fun also.

37:12.731 --> 37:15.233
The weight you have here
and the balance works.

37:15.233 --> 37:18.486
Overall, sir,
your nagamaki will KEAL.

37:18.486 --> 37:22.073
‐ Thanks.
‐ Next up is the strength test.

37:22.073 --> 37:23.324
Dave?

37:23.324 --> 37:24.993
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.993 --> 37:26.578
‐ Now, to test the strength

37:26.578 --> 37:28.079
and overall
construction of your blades,

37:28.079 --> 37:29.914
I'll be chopping
into this bamboo.

37:29.914 --> 37:31.249
Now, this test is not about

37:31.249 --> 37:33.084
what your blades do
to the bamboo.

37:33.084 --> 37:35.253
What the bamboo
does to your blades.

37:35.253 --> 37:36.921
Braxton, you're up first.
You ready?

37:36.921 --> 37:39.007
‐ I'm ready.

37:39.007 --> 37:45.972
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:45.972 --> 37:49.017
[shouting]

37:49.017 --> 37:55.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:01.279 --> 38:02.614
‐ [sighs]

38:02.614 --> 38:04.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:04.616 --> 38:06.117
‐ All right, Braxton,

38:06.117 --> 38:07.702
as far as what the bamboo
did to your blade,

38:07.702 --> 38:09.621
it did nothing.

38:09.621 --> 38:13.166
There's no deflections, rolls,
chips, anything on this blade.

38:13.166 --> 38:14.793
It's as sharp as when
I picked it up.

38:14.793 --> 38:16.503
Nicely done.
It's a very strong blade.

38:16.503 --> 38:18.129
Good job.
‐ Thank you so much.

38:18.129 --> 38:20.632
‐ All right, Jake, you ready?
‐ Let's do it.

38:20.632 --> 38:27.597
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:29.182 --> 38:31.976
‐ [shouting]

38:31.976 --> 38:38.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:44.155 --> 38:45.740
All right, so your edge,

38:45.740 --> 38:47.367
just as sharp
as when it started.

38:47.367 --> 38:49.494
There are no chips,
rolls, defamation.

38:49.494 --> 38:52.997
It sliced
right through the bamboo.

38:52.997 --> 38:57.001
Your handle is a little wide
this way for me,

38:57.001 --> 38:59.003
but the fact
that it's leaned this way

38:59.003 --> 39:03.132
and that that wrap's so nice
and comfortable evens it out.

39:03.132 --> 39:04.342
Well done.
‐ Thank you.

39:04.342 --> 39:06.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:06.427 --> 39:08.179
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

39:08.179 --> 39:10.181
we know your blades can KEAL.
We know they're strong.

39:10.181 --> 39:12.559
Now it's time to find out
how sharp they are.

39:12.559 --> 39:14.936
Now, unlike the strength test,
this is all about

39:14.936 --> 39:18.106
what your edge will do
to these different materials,

39:18.106 --> 39:21.860
from the tatami,
the melons, or the sandbags.

39:21.860 --> 39:23.361
Braxton, you're up first.
Are you ready for this?

39:23.361 --> 39:24.696
‐ I'm ready.

39:24.696 --> 39:31.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:33.872 --> 39:40.879
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:49.929 --> 39:52.807
‐ All right, Braxton,
your edge had no issues at all

39:52.807 --> 39:54.559
cutting through
the tatami mats,

39:54.559 --> 39:56.060
cuts the melon easily,

39:56.060 --> 39:58.271
and on the sandbags,
it will cut through.

39:58.271 --> 40:01.524
Overall, sir, your weapon,
it will cut.

40:01.524 --> 40:04.235
‐ Thank you.
‐ Jake, your turn. You ready?

40:04.235 --> 40:05.737
‐ Let's do it.

40:05.737 --> 40:12.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:22.921 --> 40:29.928
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:31.179 --> 40:32.597
‐ All right, Jake,
let's talk about

40:32.597 --> 40:34.933
your nagamaki right here,
razor‐sharp.

40:34.933 --> 40:37.936
It cuts easily on the tatami,
cuts the melons,

40:37.936 --> 40:41.272
and just off the orders of
the corners, it cut it easily.

40:41.272 --> 40:43.149
Overall, sir, it will cut.

40:43.149 --> 40:44.609
‐ Thank you.

40:44.609 --> 40:46.277
‐ This is gonna be
very hard for us.

40:46.277 --> 40:49.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:49.280 --> 40:52.784
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges have
made their final decision.

40:52.784 --> 40:54.619
The new "Forged in Fire"
champion is...

40:54.619 --> 40:57.288
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:57.288 --> 40:59.123
Braxton, congratulations.

40:59.123 --> 41:00.833
You're the "Forged in Fire"
champion.

41:00.833 --> 41:03.336
Jake, unfortunately,
your blade didn't make the cut.

41:03.336 --> 41:05.129
Ben Abbott's
gonna tell you why.

41:05.129 --> 41:06.714
‐ Well, Jake,
you should be proud.

41:06.714 --> 41:08.841
You made a beautiful
and effective weapon,

41:08.841 --> 41:11.219
and for us, this came down
to the finest of points.

41:11.219 --> 41:13.221
The fact that your blade
wasn't quite as finished

41:13.221 --> 41:15.473
and we had a slight preference
for Braxton's handle

41:15.473 --> 41:17.141
and that's the reason
we're sending you home.

41:17.141 --> 41:20.144
‐ Jake, please
surrender your blade.

41:20.144 --> 41:22.355
<i>‐ I think the time frame</i>
<i>that I had to build</i>

41:22.355 --> 41:24.983
my second blade
definitely had a factor in it.

41:24.983 --> 41:26.818
<i>I may not be the</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

41:26.818 --> 41:28.319
but I feel like
I accomplished a lot

41:28.319 --> 41:31.656
<i>and earned the privilege</i>
<i>to be here.</i>

41:31.656 --> 41:33.157
‐ Braxton, congratulations.

41:33.157 --> 41:34.993
You're the
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:34.993 --> 41:36.995
and that's a title that comes
with a check for 10 grand.

41:36.995 --> 41:38.663
Good job.

41:38.663 --> 41:41.332
<i>‐ I feel great about</i>
<i>what I've accomplished.</i>

41:41.332 --> 41:44.210
I'm still shaking.
It was an awesome experience,

41:44.210 --> 41:46.671
and I proved that I can hang
with the big guys.

41:46.671 --> 41:51.801
<i>♪ ♪</i>
